## [18] "tips.csv"
tip<-read.csv("tips.csv")

table(tip$size)
## 
##   1   2   3   4   5   6 
##   4 156  38  37   5   4
prop.table(table(tip$size)) 
## 
##          1          2          3          4          5          6 
## 0.01639344 0.63934426 0.15573770 0.15163934 0.02049180 0.01639344
round(prop.table(table(tip$size)),3)*100 #round to three 
## 
##    1    2    3    4    5    6 
##  1.6 63.9 15.6 15.2  2.0  1.6
mydf<-data.frame(
  size=1:6,
  freq=c(4,156,38,37,5,4),
  perc=c(1.6,63.9,15.6,15.2,2.0,1.6)
)
mydf
##   size freq perc
## 1    1    4  1.6
## 2    2  156 63.9
## 3    3   38 15.6
## 4    4   37 15.2
## 5    5    5  2.0
## 6    6    4  1.6
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(data=mydf,aes(x=size,ymax=perc,ymin=0))+
  geom_linerange()

#dot plot--numerical, small to moderate size dataset
ggplot(data=tip,aes(x=tip))+
  geom_dotplot(method = "histodot",dotsize = .5,binwidth=0.5)   #dot plot

#box plot, for numerical data
ggplot(data=tip,aes(y=tip))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  coord_flip()    #transfer to horizontal

#box plot by group
ggplot(data=tip,aes(x=day,y=tip))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  coord_flip()   #the dots are outliers, the line is not maximum if there are outliers

#histogram --large data set
ggplot(data=tip,aes(x=tip))+
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(data=tip, aes(x=tip))+
  geom_histogram(color="red",fill="white",bins=10)  #change color and fill

#give us ten bars, the width of bins are automatically decided
#scatter plot- two numerical variables
ggplot(data=tip,aes(x=totbill,y=tip))+
  geom_point(col="blue",size=2,shape=3)     #set x&y variables, color&size

?pch  #got menus for the patterns
  
#correlation of determination r
cor(tip$totbill,tip$tip)  #put in the x and y, get the r=0.68
## [1] 0.6757341
#Interpret the value
#There is a moderate strong linear positive relationship between 
#the total bill and the tips
rsq<-cor(tip$totbill,tip$tip)^2
rperc<-rsq*100
print(c(rperc,"% of tips can be explained by the linear relationship"))
## [1] "45.6616586351676"                                     
## [2] "% of tips can be explained by the linear relationship"
